questiontext.text:
Image source: http://www.forestwander.com


When a camera lens is defocussed, which of the following statements is true:

{1:MCV:~The image appears sharper.#Incorrect~Multiplying the Fourier transform of the image by a constant will affect the smoothness of the image.#Incorrect~=The spectrum of spatial frequencies contained within the image becomes narrower.#You got it!~The camera's "point response function" becomes narrower.#Incorrect}

generalfeedback.text:
When a camera records an image, the image represents a convolution between the ideal image (i.e. a perfect image of the object(s) being observed) and the point response function (PRF) of the camera. The PRF is the image obtained when the camera takes a picture of a point object, e.g. a very sharp point of light. If the camera is well focussed, then the PRF is very narrow. If the camera is unfocussed, then the PRF is broad, and the convolution process causes the image to be a very blurred representation of the object(s) being observed. Defocussing causes high frequencies to be lost from the PRF, and thus the recorded image also lacks high frequencies.

Hence the spectrum of spatial frequencies contained within the image becomes narrower.
